snippet.textDisplay:
Nissan needs to differentiate themselves from the competition instead of maintaining this image that they are a budget alternative to Toyota. Nissan came in as an underdog and over half a century later, they're still trying to play "Catch up"? Where i'm from, when someone says "Nissan" I think about the R34 Skyline, 250Z, the Silvia. Nearly nobody thinks about the Navara, the Titan, the Sentra, matter of fact if we do think about "Luxury" cars from Nissan, just one comes to mind and that's then Laurel Medalist edition. Nobody thinks "Hey, i'm gonna buy a nice pickup today" and get a Navara, they think "Hey, I want to get a cheap pickup that would do the job" and get a Navara and that's not that many people. Where I am, Nissan is not known to have the most durable parts, they are known to have among the cheapest, and that is the main reason why I will not buy a Nissan, they don't fair well in everyday use, especially not on the sub-par roads that we have here in Trinidad.

So in my opinion, Nissan needs to.

1) Focus on their most recognized products like the "Z" series, the "Skyline" the "Laurel" the "Sunny"
2) Make their designs look less like they were made to be made by robots, meaning stop making them so damn bloated looking and start bringing back the edges.
3) Make the parts more durable

Then, I, personally will consider buying one, but I don't mean it in a way that if I make one single purchase it would save a conglomerate, the way I think about it is that if I can think about it this way, who's to say that others don't feel the same way? I don't hate Nissan. I love the Skyline, I don't really like the R35 design though, at least not the front end and the back looks similar to a Mitsubishi Mirage.

snippet.textDisplay:
Actually, I have resided in Japan for 11 years and I have personally experienced the exact same kind of setup/character assassination/rigged process that Ghosn has experienced. Furthermore, I have worked for three different Courts and have a pretty good idea of how things should work in any modern democratic country, and, frankly, there is no justification for holding a retirement aged. Very informative video, Nissan should make cars that are reliable as they once did in the beginning years.
Remove the stupid CVT bring back Auto manual transmission paired to 6 or 8 speed gears, and optional 6 -speed manual for the true enthusiast on any make of their line ups from Sentra, frontier, to Altima and Maxima.
Bring back the V-6 engines on the Altima , let the customers have the option of having a base V-6 motor to a nismo tuned motor mated to a transmission auto manual or manual, prices will vary definitely.
Nissan is innovative, it makes me wonder why Hyundai already offers most of what higher end luxury cars have as a ridiculous price option. On safety , to it's cars parking itself autonomously.
Nissan should revise its GTR and give it the option of having a manual transmission, other than it's dual clutch transmission. Provide options or packages that enthusiasts or customers want specially for a car selling at 100K I'd like to have a sunroof/moonroof, and manual transmission if I want a GTR.

Nissan can offer the option of T-top or targa or sunroof/moonroof for enthusiasts or customers want.
Lastly Nissan should make their new upcoming Z be able to be tuned with aftermarket parts from it's base engine v-6 to it's nismo tuned v-6. The idea of a Mercedes 4 cylinder will throw me off into buying Nissan's upcoming Z. I own a 2012 Lexus ISF V-8 that only has ppe headers at around 420 or so bhp. I enjoy it's 8 speed Automanual transmission, for me it would be more fun if it was a 6-speed manual transmission. But it is what it is... Nissan should redesign it's line up, because the maxima is starting to look like a 4 door spaceship with a pick up truck like front end.. the distinction show's it's a Nissan alright a uglier new Nissan.
